   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## **Project Challenges and Difficulty**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "587f3d0d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since being developed in 2015, the U-Net architecture now has thousands of variants, each tailored to specific contexts and niches within image segmentation.  Despite its rapid and widespread adoption -- particularly within the biomedical imaging community -- little is presently understood about its mathematical framework or why it has superior performance in both efficiency and accuracy.\n",
    "\n",
    "In our research, only one paper -- a recent pre-print available on arXiv -- attempts to seriously detail the U-Net mathematically (see `Source 4` above).  In this project, we present the original U-Net architecture, alongside a couple of popular variants (see the `Actual Implementation of Code` section and accompanying discussion).  We also demonstrate its effectiveness via figures (see the `Clean Figures` section).  We therefore demonstrate the immense difficulty in understanding why the U-Net works and how it does the \"magic\" it does through code, plots and accompanying discussions throughout the notebook, as well as via our presentation.  An accompanying summary then follows (see the `Approach Taken / Lessons Learned` section)."
   ]
  },
